Track stretches for miles in each direction, creating a network of trains that frequently pass through The Village of Dolton. Common warning horns of freight trains echo throughout the southern suburb everyday, every hour, and during one of many community events of the year—Steppin at the Fountain. Where on a nearby hilltop of the Dolton Public Library, a young girl dances to the rhythm of her own imagination.

On Sibley Boulevard, Dolton’s main commercial strip, newsstands that once offered job and housing information sit empty, replaced with “For Rent” signs. Deindustrialization throughout the south suburbs decades ago eliminated thousands of private-sector jobs.

Harvard University graduates Robert, 28, Scott, 28, and Nick, 32, at a wedding reception on a private island off the coast of Cape Cod, Massachusetts, 1994. People travel by foot or horse-drawn carriage on the car-free island, owned by the same prominent Boston family for more than a century.

The sixteenth-century Château des Rochers-Sévigné, Vitré, France, 1987. It was home to the seventeenth-century writer Madame de Sévigné, who immortalized it in her famous letters to her daughter. It still belongs to descendants of the marquise.

The huntmaster at the traditional lunch following the hunt on horseback, Normandy, France, 1987. This 200-year-old club used to host weekly hunts on Tuesdays and Saturdays. Now that many members work during the week, the hunt is held only on weekends.
A maid, orphaned as a child and taken into the household of an aristocratic family, serves a traditional Sunday lunch, Autun, France, 1987.

A “rallye” party at the Jockey Club, one of Paris’s most rarefied private clubs, 1987. Associations of noble families organize these parties to allow aristocratic youth to meet others of their class. For such events the Association of French Nobility can provide formal attire as a charitable service to those who may not be able to afford it.

Irish Itinerants series, Galway, Ireland, 1991. Known as “Travellers” in Ireland, this distinct ethnic group numbers around 25,000 people. Their traditionally nomadic way of life marginalizes them in Irish society.
Children at a wedding, Irish Itinerants series, Galway, Ireland, 1991. Although Travellers often live in impoverished conditions, weddings are elaborate affair.
Irish Itinerants series, Galway, Ireland, 1991. Until 1960, 95% of Travellers had no permanent home, but since then the Irish government has made efforts to settle them in caravan camps.

An Untouchable by the Ganges River, Varanasi, India, 1986. Since contact with corpses would contaminate members of higher castes such as Brahmins, only Untouchables are permitted to cremate bodies by the holy river.
Maya boys playing, Nabenchauk, Chiapas, Mexico, 1991.
A Maya curing ceremony, Nabenchauk, Chiapas, Mexico, 1991.

Children walk past a burned building in the aftermath of riots sparked by the acquittal of four police officers who were videotaped beating Rodney King, Los Angeles, 1992. The unrest, which spread from South Central L.A. to other parts of the city, left 53 people dead and caused an estimated $1 billion worth of property damage.
A police officer arresting a man during the L.A. riots, Los Angeles, 1992. Before the riots were over, 13,500 troops from the National Guard, Army, and Marines had been called in to restore order.
Defense attorney Robert Shapiro at O. J. Simpson’s trial for the murder of his ex-wife, Nicole Brown Simpson, and her friend, Ron Goldman, Los Angeles, 1995.
The burned-out landscape of Laguna Beach following the most destructive wildfire ever to strike affluent Orange County, 1993.

Maralyn Brady in the wreckage of her home after the Northridge earthquake, Santa Monica, California, 1994. The 6.7 magnitude quake killed 57 people, left 9,000 injured, and cost the state up to $40 billion

Students protest against Proposition 187, Los Angeles, 1994. Proposition 187 was a California ballot initiative designed to prevent illegal immigrants’ access to state-funded services, including education and health care. Implementation was blocked, and a federal judge ruled it unconstitutional in 1997.
Fires burning during the L.A. riots, Los Angeles, 1992.

A volunteer search party looking for bodies, several had already been found here along the Chattahoochee River, Atlanta, Georgia
At night there is a curfew, a police patrol stops black children and warns them to stay off the streets, Atlanta, Georgia

Pilgrimage to Meron on Laq Ba'omer Day, Jerusalem, Israel

The sign reads: Believe in God. It's the duty of Russia, China, and the Arabs to help the people of Israel in Zion. Jerusalem the homeland of Israel and the Bible. During a protest of the Orthodox Jews in Jerusalem, Israel
Smoke cloud from explosion during Yom Kippur War, Israel

Some marriages on Brick Lane are still arranged on the strict basis of financial support: here a 64-year-old man accepted a young girl from his native village as a wife to ensure her family’s survival in Bangladesh, London, England
Some Asian girls here get the taste for free speech, once out of the situation of Bangladesh villages, London, England
This Asian mother is courageous enough to take English lessons, London, England
A family of eight puts mattresses together on the floor at night and stacks them up by day in order to move about the tiny rat-infested apartment, London, England
British troops arrest bloody demonstrator during riots in Roman Catholic Bogside area, Londonderry, North Ireland
A couple looks at rubble and people in street, North Ireland
In the Protestant area of Londonderry, the walls are adorned with Union Jacks and painting of William of Orange, Londonderry, North Ireland

Ted Kennedy speaks and listens to the complaints of the veterans and youth. All the major democratic possible presidential candidates for 1972 were seen in Washington talking to these people. The war and its end is considered to be the major political fight of the forthcoming presidential campaign. What the outcome will be depends on how the people's opinion will develop, Washington DC
Demonstrators marching with “Connecticut Vietnam Veterans against the war” banner, Washington DC
Women watch demonstrators performing reenactment on sidewalk, Veterans Against War demonstration, Washington DC
Man with guitar next to line of demonstrators at Veterans Against War protest, Washington DC
Protestors in wheelchairs, Veterans Against the War demonstration, Washington DC
Among the crowd, a mother of a dead veteran with a shirt bearing the decorations won by her son in Vietnam, Veterans Against the War Protest, Washington DC
Woman carrying framed medals during Veterans Against the War demonstration, Washington DC

Part of the pile of medals, decorations, war mementos and good conduct certificates which have been discarded in disgust and anger against the Vietnam War, Veterans Against the War demonstration, Washington DC

Deadly Game: Having a good time, captured Viet Cong guerrillas demonstrate an attack for their South Vietnamese captors here recently. Twenty-five Viet Cong surrendered here on October 1st, Thang Binh

Deadly Serious: Determination is shown on the faces of these North Vietnamese women as they practice at their anti-aircraft emplacement in the Thanh Hoa Province, 75 miles south of Hanoi, September 1960

Looking At A New Home: Vietnamese orphans crowd the windows of a World Airways DC8 as it flies them to their new home — the United States. Fifty-five of the children were airlifted from Saigon to the U.S. where most will meet their new families

A Helping Hand: Vietnamese orphans, whose parents were killed by the Viet Cong, are receiving food and medical aid in this photo Barschow sent to his parents. He had asked them to seek help for the orphanage

Passage Of History: Different modes of transport whirl past the Roman Catholic Basilica, background, a relic of Cambodia’s French colonial history, in Phnom Penh. Troops on bus are returning to capital after road-clearing military operation. Young men in foreground ride in a three-wheeled “cyclo,” still a much used vehicle in Phnom Penh
Loaded For Trouble: a Cambodian soldier carries 30 caliber machine gun, with ammunition ready to use, during recent fighting in the vicinity of Saang, Cambodia

Doctors and medical corpsmen worked in vain to save the life of Pfc. Arthur A. Shelton aboard the Caribou transport bearing him to a naval hospital in Nha Trang, Vietnam. Pfc. Shelton had been with his gunner outfit only three days
School children in Ninh Hoa, South Vietnam, wave and smile at American helicopter pilots

Helps Refugee: An elderly South Vietnamese refugee is helped up river bank at My Chanh, 20 miles north of the old imperial city of Hue, after fleeing from Quang Tri which was abandoned to the North Vietnamese forces earlier this month. My Chanh is the new government defense line

Wui Xuan Thuy (center) North Vietnam’s chief delegate to peace talks with the United States arrived today at Le Bourget airfield coming from Moscow and had a warm welcome by a crowd of about 300 Vietnamese and French men, Paris

Trooper with Brigade of the U.S. 25th Infantry Division, which was part of Operation Oregon, searching for Viet Cong 325 miles northeast of Saigon. The villagers use this method of drying to preserve the potatoes until the next harvest. The village was almost completely abandoned when the U.S. soldiers arrived

This is the palace in Phnom Penh where Prince Norodom Sihanouk once ruled Cambodia. It is now a museum under the republican government but many Cambodians are expressing nostalgia for the “good old days” of the Monarchy two years ago

North Vietnam President Interviewed: President Ho Chi Minh of North Vietnam who will be 74 on May 19th is shown during interview in Hanoi with Wilfred S. Burchett, a Communist-oriented Australian-born newspaperman who works now in Moscow. Ho said it would be sheer stupidity for the United States and South Vietnam to carry the war against his Communist Viet Cong forces into the north. Burchett made these pictures of Ho during the interview which took place in mid-April and was made available after Burchett’s return to Moscow

Thai troops arrive in Vietnam: some of the 1500 members of Thailand’s Black Panther Infantry Division disembark from the United States Navy vessel Okanogan at the American Army Newport port facility just north of Saigon today. They are the first of the division’s 12,000 soldiers to be stationed in South Vietnam

Softening Up The Enemy: still smoking cannon of the 9th artillery battery, 25th division is quickly reloaded during action near the Cambodian border in South Vietnam as the artillerymen supported 10,000 U.S. and Korean infantrymen searching for North Vietnamese regulars who had slipped over the border into the central Vietnamese highlands

Chatting With Vietnamese: Providing security for a medical detail to aid Vietnamese civilians here January 20th, 1970, the leader of a Combined Reconnaissance Intelligence Patrol, Sgt. Cecil Strictland (no hometown available), chats with local youngsters

Says A Prayer: A Vietnamese woman kneels to pray shortly before she and 99 other Vietnamese civilians were allegedly forced to march towards the Viet Cong-held village of Saang, Cambodia April 21st, 1970 with leaflets urging the Viet Cong to leave Cambodia. A short time later, the civilians were caught in a crossfire between the VC and Cambodian forces. An unknown number of civilians were killed and wounded in the crossfire

Blasting Support For A Leatherneck Patrol: U.S. Marine artillery blasts from Firebase Cunningham in support of a Marine patrol which made contact with North Vietnamese more than 430 yards away, March 2, 1969. The firebase is one of several hilltop bases along the Laos border in the northwestern corner of South Vietnam

Travel Power: The North Vietnamese have conditioned themselves for a war which, according to official Hanoi predictions, may last 10 to 20 years. While the people live their daily lives under anti-aircraft fortifications and machine guns in upper-story windows throughout the towns, commerce and industry continue. Despite the war and the bombings, this tramline in Hanoi continues a cheap means of transportation to the populace. One woman is seated, left, on the opening to a bomb shelter

Pedal Power: Through North Vietnam is a young nation, with 17 million people, more than half, 10 million, are beneath the age of thirty and, of these, 4 million are of military age (15-30.) In downtown Hanoi, along the main shopping center, the daytime street is nearly deserted as the people work for their government. Vehicles, a prized possession, are rare, and on this vehicle can be seen special adapters for night-driving while a bicyclist pedals along. In the background is Hanoi’s National Theater and Opera House, closed now due to bombing

Prisoners Of War: These American pilots who are to be freed by North Vietnam were photographed in North Vietnam by the Washington correspondent of the St. Louis Post Dispatch, Richard Dudman. They are from left: Lt.jg Markham Ligon Gartley, Lt.jg Norris Alphonzo Charles and Major Edward Knight Elias

Begs For Mercy: a Cambodian Communist soldier begs for mercy during interrogation by South Vietnamese soldiers after his capture near Krek, Cambodia, about 10 miles west of the border with South Vietnam. He was later taken to South Vietnamese field headquarters in Krek

Bandages cover head of a young refugee at Cho Ray Hospital in Cholon, Saigon’s Chinatown. Civilians paid a dear price in fighting to drive Communist invaders out of the area. Many homes were destroyed

Ted’s Foreign Affair: The plight of refugees in Vietnam is one area of foreign affairs on which Senator Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts has worked. On matters of policy in foreign affairs he usually defers to brother Robert, senator from New York, Here Ted Kennedy, left, jokes with South Vietnamese Brig. General Nguyen Chanh Thi, I Corps commander, during a visit to Phuoc Thanh refugee center near Danang on a Vietnamese tour

Lying Low: hugging the ground under Viet Cong sniper fire, men of the U.S. 1st Infantry Division look for source of enemy fire. Tank leading the unit prepares to fire its 50-caliber machine gun toward brush. Soldiers were on an operation last week near Long Thanh in South Vietnam, about 40 miles west of Saigon

Safe Return: Australian soldiers sit in armored personnel carrier on their way back to their command post following a three-day operation in South Vietnam’s Phuoc Tuy Province, South of Saigon. The troops are with the 7th Royal Australian Regiment which has been in Vietnam since 1965

Use Taxi For Protection: with bullet shells littering the ground, South Vietnamese military police crouch behind a bullet-scarred taxi while exchanging fire with Viet Cong infiltrators in Cholon, the Chinese sector of Saigon

Air Search For Viet Cong: U.S. helicopters loaded with 1st Cavalry reconnaissance troops patrol along the South China Sea beach, scouting for a Viet Cong squad that had been sighted earlier in the area. The 1st Cavalry Division is conducting a three-month operation in South Vietnam’s Binh Dinh province about 300 miles northeast of Saigon

U.S. Marines on the 196th Light Infantry Brigade debark from giant C130 transports after being airlifted here from Da Nang April 11, 1972 to bolster defenses of this northernmost American outpost in South Vietnam. U.S. Artillery battery and force of 400 American infantrymen, some scheduled to go home, were flown into combat area below DMZ to guard American installations against the 12-day-old North Vietnamese offensive, Phu Bai, South Vietnam

Welcomed Home: Lieutenant Commander Porter Halyburton is greeted Friday at the Atlanta airport by his wife, Martha, and 8-year-old daughter, Dabney. The Navy flier from Tucker, Georgia was a prisoner of war in North Vietnam for seven years
Night Work: Around the clock Marine Aircraft Group 16 mechanics and technicians at the Marble Mountain Air Facility near Da Nang, labor to prepare their aircraft for the next day’s missions

Looking After The Little Ones: An Australian nurse, left, aids one of the South Vietnamese war orphans at Bangkok airport during stopover for transfer to charter Qantas 747 jumbo jet for the flight to Sydney, Australia

Arrive with New Viet Cong Peace Plan: Tram Buu Kiem, right, representative of Viet Cong’s National Liberation front, arrives at International Conference Center in Paris for peace negotiations. He advanced a 10-point peace plan calling for establishment of a coalition government and leaving to the Vietnamese people the question of dealing with Vietnam armed forces. At left is Kiem’s deputy, Mrs. Nguyen Thi Binh. In center is an interpreter

Remain Cool In Heat of Battle: Platoon leader 2nd Lt. Hector Colon of Chicago, left, and Sgt. Johnnie English of San Antonio, Texas go over some maps in South Vietnam’s War Zone C. Colon’s platoon was the last of Bravo Company to be evacuated from the jungle after a day of patrolling and was caught in the close quarter firefight with Communist troops. The men of Colon’s platoon were credited with killing 60 of the enemy of the estimated 500 that surrounded them

An Officer And A Gentleman: A lieutenant with the U.S. 101st Airborne Division’s third brigade manning Fire Base Catherine adds a touch of class to the uniform of the day by donning a tie. Fire Base Catherine is located south of the DMZ in South Vietnam’s most northern province

A Rockfest at Firebase Catherine: amplified guitars, a saxophone, drums and a electric organ backing up a GI “soul singer” set the sultry air throbbing at Firebase Catherine, dug in on a hill south of the Demilitarized Zone in Vietnam. Musicians and fans alike were members of the Third Brigade of the 101st Division. Around the outdoor amphitheatre were the symbols of the war-- wooden bunkers, sandbags, a helicopter-- but the GIs were momentarily “at home” with their own music. The firebase situated on a hilltop, provides artillery cover for low-lying field missions

Embarking: South Vietnamese troops, observed from the window of a Sea Knight helicopter, prepare to embark aboard a Marine Medium Helicopter Squadron 165 transport helicopter at a jumping-off point south of Da Nang. They will be airlifted into an area southwest of Da Nang in search of enemy forces

The battle scarred village of Sa Huynh on South Vietnam’s central coast on February 28th, 1973, where fighting has destroyed many homes since the cease-fire began, and touched off charges of violations between the Saigon Government and the Viet Cong. Haggling stalled the joint military commission’s agreement to investigate

Men Of War: As Two U.S. Marines rest at Son-Thang, nearby water serves as a kind of canvas for a symbolic image of the U.S. commitment in Vietnam. The leathernecks rest briefly during an operation against Viet Cong units about 35 miles southwest of the big U.S. base at Da Nang

American women try to comfort their children as they wait at Hue Airport for evacuation to the Da Nang airbase because of unrest at Hue. Seventy-two Americans were airlifted to Da Nang and Phu Bai, both U.S. Marine enclaves

Major Brown Has A Job To Do. He Wants To Be Able To Be Ready To Do It Well: The war in Vietnam is a close war, the kind of war where a man’s training and determination mean more than all the firepower in the nation’s arsenal. It’s a portable war — you carry what you need into the jungles to meet the enemy. Above and at right, Major Brown learns how to aim an artillery piece. Below, he listens as an Air Force officers explains how to call for air support while under fire

The mountain tribes (above) live in houses raised on stilts. Always they have lived a nomadic life. Now they drift with the war. Tanks clank along the road. A cow gives bith. Spring comes and the mountain brooks swell with clear water… life goes on

This resort beach has been the home for 518 Vietnamese refugees since their boat landed on May 28th, 1979. Hygienic facilities are rare and the Malaysian government has provided rice but now threatens to repair the boats and send the refugees out to sea and an uncertain destiny

The Ins And Outs Of Viet Cong Life: A typical Vietnamese hut, top, in a Viet Cong campsite appears ordinary enough to the passerby. Actually it is camouflage for a Viet Cong bomb shelter, bottom, which may extend to tunnels and other shelters. Here, Viet Cong soldiers, one a woman, play cards inside the shelter. Photo made by freelance photographer Roger Pic for Look Magazine

Smiling Refugees: These Vietnamese children smile as they get their first look at the military barracks that will be their homes on Guam for the next few months. They were on the first flight to land Wednesday at Guam under Operation New Life

Cambodian Casualty: A wounded Cambodian soldier is carried through rice paddies by friend after they had been ambushed by North Vietnamese troops at Samrong, Cambodia, 10 miles west of Phnom Penh on November 30th, 1971. The Cambodian troops were attempting to clear enemy soldiers from positions they have used to fire artillery rounds into Phnom Penh

City life looks normal in this view of a street in Ho Chi Minh City, formerly Saigon, made about a month ago by Japanese journalist Kyohiko Takizawa of Asahi Shimbun. The newsman joined a Japanese business group for an inspection tour of reunified Vietnam

Reports To President: General Andrew Goodpaster, deputy commander of U.S. forces in Vietnam, reports to President Johnson on Vietnam fighting during a meeting at the White House today, December 24, 1968

Precious Load: A young mother carries her two children in a basket suspended from a carrying pole as she and other refugees flee fighting around the city of Quang Tri, 19 miles south of the demilitarized zone. The refugees use any means they can to get themselves and their few possessions out of the battle areas

War Comes To Ang Tasom: Cambodian troops patrol the crossroads town of the Ang Tasom. Reports April 26th, 1970 indicated the town was still the center of fighting between the Cambodians and Viet Cong, although the Cambodian government announced it had scored its first victory over the Vietnamese by gaining control of the town

Suspected Viet Cong: a Cambodian soldier prepares to slam the butt of his rifle against a suspected Viet Cong in the District town of Ang Tasom. The town, six miles west of Takeo, had earlier been attacked by the Viet Cong

Caring For A Casualty: While the battles of Khe Sanh, Vietnam, go on, a steady flow of wounded are rushed into the underground hospital bunker for emergency treatment sufficient until removal to a rear area hospital, March 8th, 1968. Though more than 1,000 men have been patched up and evacuated, the quarters are continually crowded, causing stretchers to be slung, four high, from wall pegs and rope attached to the ceiling. A wounded soldier, receiving transfusions, is tended to by a flak-jacketed corpsman in the hospital bunker of Khe Sanh

The St. George building stood at the northwest corner of Beekman and Cliff Streets.  Built as a warehouse in 1870, it retained the name of a series of churches that had stood on the spot since the mid-18th century.

The west side of Gold Street between Ann and Beekman Streets. The metal front of this type of building was ordered in sections from catalogs.  An identical building, only a section less in length, stood on the corner of Beekman and Pearl Streets.

100 Gold Street seen from the remains of the Tribune Building.  Built as an experiment in 1926, 100 Gold has provided offices for both the FBI and New York Traffic Commissioner Barnes.  It was the first reinforced concrete structure of its height built and demolished in New York.

Huey and his crew inside 81 Beekman Street.  An elevator is demolished.   The heavy sandstone window blocks must be dropped, like everything else, inside the building and not onto the street.  Huey could bring down a loft building at the rate of a floor a day.
A burner is lifted to cut the bolts in the cast-iron front of 82 Beekman Street.  The cast iron is then smashed to pieces with a sledgehammer.

It took over six months to bring down the fourteen stories of 100 Gold.  The hand-mixed concrete had to be smashed with a punch, and then the steel reinforcement rods had to be cut by burners.  With all the buildings disappearing around it 100 Gold seemed somehow to always still be there.  Its last two floors were pulverized by a shovel and ball.
Beekman Street subbasement.  The demolition contract requires that the building be3 brought down to street level.  Basements and tunnels are filled in and left buried beneath vacant lots.
